1
00:00:05,932 --> 00:00:08,459
Good afternoon, welcome.

2
00:00:08,459 --> 00:00:12,552
My name is Henke, and I'm a freelance composer for mobile

3
00:00:12,552 --> 00:00:13,775
and VR games and films.

4
00:00:14,183 --> 00:00:16,885
In the past, I also had co-composing credits

5
00:00:16,885 --> 00:00:19,688
as an additional composer for some of these nice games.

6
00:00:19,688 --> 00:00:23,430
And I wanted to share with you the findings

7
00:00:23,430 --> 00:00:24,971
of the annual Game Audio Survey for 2017,

8
00:00:24,971 --> 00:00:28,214
sponsored by the Game Audio Network Guild

9
00:00:28,214 --> 00:00:29,895
and Game Sound Con.

10
00:00:29,895 --> 00:00:33,638
We're very grateful to Brian Schmidt

11
00:00:33,638 --> 00:00:36,300
for doing these amazing surveys.

12
00:00:36,300 --> 00:00:39,342
72% of the game composers also create sound effects.

13
00:00:39,642 --> 00:00:43,546
50% of all game composers also provide audio integration.

14
00:00:43,546 --> 00:00:46,989
So this is my message to all emerging composers

15
00:00:46,989 --> 00:00:49,812
in the audience, and I mean this from my heart.

16
00:00:49,812 --> 00:00:53,875
Learn sound design to expand your job possibilities.

17
00:00:53,875 --> 00:00:57,539
Also, learn sound design to improve your own skills

18
00:00:57,539 --> 00:00:59,541
and craft as a composer for games.

19
00:01:00,505 --> 00:01:04,306
Having sound design skills makes you a more valuable collaborator

20
00:01:04,306 --> 00:01:05,666
to game developers.

21
00:01:05,666 --> 00:01:10,367
You could get in-house jobs and build the career more organically,

22
00:01:10,367 --> 00:01:13,088
starting out as a sound designer for a game company

23
00:01:13,088 --> 00:01:16,008
and then gradually composing as well.

24
00:01:16,008 --> 00:01:19,209
Many sound designers have full-time staff positions.

25
00:01:19,209 --> 00:01:23,950
On another hand, most composers are freelancers,

26
00:01:23,950 --> 00:01:25,210
unless they're also sound designers.

27
00:01:25,910 --> 00:01:31,175
So, I started out as a composer, so I learned all of this.

28
00:01:31,175 --> 00:01:34,618
Each game has many people working on the sound.

29
00:01:34,618 --> 00:01:37,521
Some may work on weapons, vehicles, combat, or foley.

30
00:01:37,521 --> 00:01:41,284
Others may work on ambiences, dialogue, editing, implementation.

31
00:01:41,284 --> 00:01:45,969
It's common for a game company to have a few staff audio specialists

32
00:01:45,969 --> 00:01:49,372
and also farm out other audio tasks to freelancers.

33
00:01:50,132 --> 00:01:52,774
Most indie games use only one composer.

34
00:01:52,774 --> 00:01:56,035
The composer is brought in for a few months at the end

35
00:01:56,035 --> 00:01:59,257
or the last few months of the development cycle.

36
00:01:59,257 --> 00:02:03,859
I wanted to tell you a joke from the old world.

37
00:02:03,859 --> 00:02:06,440
A son asks his son, what are you going

38
00:02:06,440 --> 00:02:07,681
to become when you grow up?

39
00:02:07,681 --> 00:02:09,762
And the son answers, I'm going to become a doctor.

40
00:02:09,762 --> 00:02:12,763
And the father says, become a dentist.

41
00:02:12,763 --> 00:02:15,704
People have 32 teeth and only one heart.

42
00:02:20,627 --> 00:02:25,771
Most opportunities for emerging composers are in a mobile and casual field,

43
00:02:25,771 --> 00:02:29,434
where having all audio skills, music, sound design, voiceover, editing,

44
00:02:29,434 --> 00:02:33,377
audio middleware in implementation could help you land a great job.

45
00:02:33,377 --> 00:02:36,280
This is why I encourage all of you to consider this path.

46
00:02:36,900 --> 00:02:40,464
Another crucial reason to learn sound design is this.

47
00:02:40,464 --> 00:02:44,648
Learning sound design improves your own craft and skills as a composer.

48
00:02:44,648 --> 00:02:47,652
So this is, I'm speaking from my personal experience,

49
00:02:47,652 --> 00:02:51,435
as a composer working on fantasy content where music, sound design,

50
00:02:51,435 --> 00:02:55,319
and voiceover always dovetail and always mesh together,

51
00:02:55,319 --> 00:02:57,021
it makes you a better game composer.

52
00:02:57,462 --> 00:03:00,745
to really know how to create diegetic and ambient sound design,

53
00:03:00,745 --> 00:03:04,688
because it's all frequencies and it all comes through the ears.

54
00:03:04,688 --> 00:03:08,852
By learning sound design, you learn how to compose around the frequencies

55
00:03:08,852 --> 00:03:11,875
of diegetic sound and tonal ambiences.

56
00:03:11,875 --> 00:03:17,761
You practice scoring hits and jump scares in horror or genre titles

57
00:03:17,761 --> 00:03:20,884
without the music smearing what the sound design is already doing.

58
00:03:21,484 --> 00:03:26,886
On the other hand, the music is going to soar in the theme, the menu, the boss battles,

59
00:03:26,886 --> 00:03:30,788
obviously, and action cinematics without dialogue.

60
00:03:30,788 --> 00:03:32,409
It was a real epiphany for me.

61
00:03:32,409 --> 00:03:35,450
I learned this from my developer friends.

62
00:03:35,450 --> 00:03:39,152
Game developers approach the hierarchy of audio like this.

63
00:03:39,152 --> 00:03:41,833
The voiceover is primary because it tells the story.

64
00:03:41,833 --> 00:03:43,373
Diegetic sound effects.

65
00:03:43,553 --> 00:03:47,295
or sound effects directly related to what's visible on the screen are secondary.

66
00:03:47,295 --> 00:03:52,637
Emotional sound design, this is kind of a loose term, is the non-diegetic such as drones,

67
00:03:52,637 --> 00:03:58,040
ambiences, which is anything that makes you feel something, is also secondary.

68
00:03:58,040 --> 00:04:01,541
And music, the diegetic music, the non-diegetic music is tertiary.

69
00:04:02,362 --> 00:04:05,762
So, in summary, I wanted...

70
00:04:05,762 --> 00:04:07,483
You'll get staff jobs in game audio,

71
00:04:07,483 --> 00:04:11,584
in game studio as a sound designer and implementer first,

72
00:04:11,584 --> 00:04:13,404
and later as a composer.

73
00:04:13,404 --> 00:04:15,905
And also, deep understanding of the sound in games

74
00:04:15,905 --> 00:04:18,646
makes you definitely a greater game composer.

75
00:04:18,646 --> 00:04:21,987
I wanted to briefly discuss one of my composing assignments.

76
00:04:21,987 --> 00:04:26,148
I scored this Mummy VR game that is an arcade game.

77
00:04:27,088 --> 00:04:29,429
And it's a shooter with zombies.

78
00:04:29,429 --> 00:04:32,191
Genre projects always have a very elaborate...

79
00:04:32,191 --> 00:04:36,034
By genre projects I mean horror, science fiction, fantasy, which I love and adore.

80
00:04:36,034 --> 00:04:38,816
So these projects always have a very elaborate soundscape.

81
00:04:38,816 --> 00:04:42,879
You have monster roars, you have fantasy creatures, voices, death,

82
00:04:42,879 --> 00:04:46,681
sound of imaginary lands, interiors, dungeons, and so on.

83
00:04:46,681 --> 00:04:49,323
So when scoring horror, I learned the hard way

84
00:04:49,323 --> 00:04:55,187
to very carefully select the frequencies, timbres, instruments, and density of my music.

85
00:04:56,468 --> 00:05:00,251
The Mummy VR is an eight minute experience.

86
00:05:00,251 --> 00:05:02,332
It had helicopter diegetic sound

87
00:05:02,332 --> 00:05:03,733
for the first four minutes throughout,

88
00:05:03,733 --> 00:05:07,835
then a continued barrage of machine gun sound effects

89
00:05:07,835 --> 00:05:09,316
for the next four minutes.

90
00:05:09,316 --> 00:05:12,478
The game had a continuous voiceover for all eight minutes,

91
00:05:12,478 --> 00:05:14,540
and my job as a composer was to figure out

92
00:05:14,540 --> 00:05:16,941
a musical solution that would dovetail

93
00:05:16,941 --> 00:05:19,423
with all sound design and the voiceover,

94
00:05:19,423 --> 00:05:21,044
and I rescored the game twice

95
00:05:21,044 --> 00:05:23,045
because my first approach failed.

96
00:05:23,045 --> 00:05:25,687
It was too busy and too noisy and too orchestral.

97
00:05:26,107 --> 00:05:32,289
So, my second approach was iconic sound for the characters, which were special forces and zombies,

98
00:05:32,289 --> 00:05:34,410
and iconic sound for the genre.

99
00:05:34,410 --> 00:05:42,714
And by iconic I mean a basic, like a basic signifier that instantly will telegraph to you who the characters are.

100
00:05:43,234 --> 00:05:47,917
So the second big challenge in VR is that all the sound comes directly from headphones,

101
00:05:47,917 --> 00:05:49,718
and usually they're crappy headphones in your brain.

102
00:05:49,718 --> 00:05:52,439
In arcades, these are conventional headphones.

103
00:05:52,439 --> 00:05:56,422
So the music needs to convey the emotions in a simple arrangement

104
00:05:56,422 --> 00:06:00,344
that's not too busy, not too complicated, and won't burn your ears.

105
00:06:00,344 --> 00:06:04,426
So this is how I approached the special forces without melody,

106
00:06:04,426 --> 00:06:06,087
and with minimal chord changes.

107
00:06:06,687 --> 00:06:09,148
with electronic arrangement that we associate

108
00:06:09,148 --> 00:06:09,928
with like the special forces.

109
00:06:09,928 --> 00:06:11,089
So I'm going to play the first half,

110
00:06:11,089 --> 00:06:12,929
well, there's no video, you'll see the still image,

111
00:06:12,929 --> 00:06:14,430
and you'll hear the music also dubbed

112
00:06:14,430 --> 00:06:15,890
with the sound design and voiceover.

113
00:06:15,890 --> 00:06:18,231
All strike team personnel report to your fields.

114
00:06:18,231 --> 00:06:19,552
Target has been spotted.

115
00:06:19,552 --> 00:06:27,454
Briefed on the target.

116
00:07:20,175 --> 00:07:26,362
And the second half of the game was shooting at zombies and a lot of

117
00:07:26,362 --> 00:07:29,926
creatures, a lot of noise. This is just a still image and I'll play just a little

118
00:07:29,926 --> 00:07:33,570
bit of the second half of the game with the zombie shooting.

119
00:09:04,847 --> 00:09:10,772
Because of the machine gun, I took out all percussion and really only had the pads and the brass,

120
00:09:10,772 --> 00:09:14,095
because otherwise it would compete and it won't be good.

121
00:09:14,095 --> 00:09:18,319
I wish you much success in your careers. Good luck and enjoy the rest of the panel. Thanks.

