00:10:39,080 --> 00:10:41,022
and you're trying to figure out how you can fit

145
00:10:41,022 --> 00:10:43,644
into this wacky world, you know,

146
00:10:43,644 --> 00:10:45,885
we'll enter a normal scenario that many of us have gone to.

147
00:10:45,885 --> 00:10:48,067
You go to LinkedIn or you hear about a job posting

148
00:10:48,067 --> 00:10:49,668
from someone and they're told,

149
00:10:49,668 --> 00:10:52,490
oh yeah, you'd be perfect for this game opening.

150
00:10:52,490 --> 00:10:54,312
Please go to it, check it out.

151
00:10:54,312 --> 00:10:56,153
And you're like, sure, how bad could this be?

152
00:10:56,633 --> 00:10:59,694
and you click on the apply now or the web link

153
00:10:59,694 --> 00:11:01,474
and you start to read all of these descriptions

154
00:11:01,474 --> 00:11:04,535
for crazy job titles and departmental needs

155
00:11:04,535 --> 00:11:07,616
and must have 14 AAA products and must know why's

156
00:11:07,616 --> 00:11:09,236
and all these other words are flashing at you

157
00:11:09,236 --> 00:11:10,556
and suddenly you're like, oh my god,

158
00:11:10,556 --> 00:11:12,557
I have no idea what I'm doing.

159
00:11:12,557 --> 00:11:14,417
I don't have 14 titles under my belt.

160
00:11:14,417 --> 00:11:17,858
I didn't go to a school for a degree in game audio

161
00:11:17,858 --> 00:11:19,118
for most of us.

162
00:11:19,118 --> 00:11:21,298
Like in my age group or older,

163
00:11:21,298 --> 00:11:23,059
there weren't game audio degrees.

164
00:11:23,059 --> 00:11:25,059
Heck, there sometimes weren't even music tech degrees

165
00:11:25,059 --> 00:11:25,799
when we went to school.

166
00:11:26,361 --> 00:11:30,624
So, it's like, what do you do when you're told, like,

167
00:11:30,624 --> 00:11:32,666
yes, this is the field you wanna go to,

168
00:11:32,666 --> 00:11:34,507
but you don't have a direct path?

169
00:11:34,507 --> 00:11:36,789
And I wanna just assure a lot of you that,

170
00:11:36,789 --> 00:11:38,450
especially those of you who have succeeded

171
00:11:38,450 --> 00:11:39,731
in hopping into the industry,

172
00:11:39,731 --> 00:11:42,673
not straight from a game path in the beginning,

173
00:11:42,673 --> 00:11:45,996
just first, keep calm, take a deep breath,

174
00:11:45,996 --> 00:11:48,038
know you're not alone, and...

175
00:11:49,338 --> 00:11:52,780
I feel like many of us like to say that everything we learn,

176
00:11:52,780 --> 00:11:55,802
especially bizarro quotes, we all learn from the movies of things to live by.

177
00:11:55,802 --> 00:11:58,704
And I find Liam Neeson is a really good example.

178
00:11:58,704 --> 00:12:02,706
Because we've all heard this quote, like, I have a very particular set of skills,

179
00:12:02,706 --> 00:12:04,628
right, from Taken, and it's my bad impression.

180
00:12:05,869 --> 00:12:10,333
And I want to remind all of us that we all have very unique sets of skills,

181
00:12:10,333 --> 00:12:15,397
and we gather these skills through life and through all of the different experiences we have.

182
00:12:15,397 --> 00:12:21,102
And often we forget that those skills can apply to dream jobs that we have,

183
00:12:21,102 --> 00:12:23,544
or jobs that we don't even know exist yet.

184
00:12:23,544 --> 00:12:26,447
So whenever you look at these giant lists of skills that are demanded for jobs,

185
00:12:26,447 --> 00:12:29,809
especially wacky new careers in the game industry,

186
00:12:29,809 --> 00:12:31,811
it's like, how do I gather all of these?

187
00:12:32,387 --> 00:12:35,128
techniques, how do I gather this experience?

188
00:12:35,128 --> 00:12:38,250
And you may be gathering it right now and you don't even know it.

189
00:12:38,250 --> 00:12:42,672
You just need to start to learn to rethink your brain process and

190
00:12:42,672 --> 00:12:46,614
know that you learn something every day if you pay attention.

191
00:12:46,614 --> 00:12:46,794
And

192
00:12:48,930 --> 00:12:51,754
You learn by doing, and often I think we forget this,

193
00:12:51,754 --> 00:12:53,076
especially when we're not kids anymore.

194
00:12:53,076 --> 00:12:55,439
We forget that we're all constantly learning.

195
00:12:55,439 --> 00:12:59,465
And we learn it from every aspect of the day,

196
00:12:59,465 --> 00:13:02,469
every job we've ever had, every mentor,

197
00:13:02,469 --> 00:13:05,173
every experience, personally, before I worked in games.

198
00:13:06,013 --> 00:13:07,755
I had many different jobs.

199
00:13:07,755 --> 00:13:10,337
I came from, I was a fall spot operator,

200
00:13:10,337 --> 00:13:12,839
boom operator for a while, I'm a chorus junkie,

201
00:13:12,839 --> 00:13:16,282
I know a lot of people around GDC actually are.

202
00:13:16,282 --> 00:13:18,463
Sing-along musician, stage manager, teaching assistant,

203
00:13:18,463 --> 00:13:20,885
I've done multimedia, I do puppetry.

204
00:13:20,885 --> 00:13:23,768
And I can assure you that I use skills

205
00:13:23,768 --> 00:13:25,689
from every single one of these jobs every day

206
00:13:25,689 --> 00:13:26,990
in my current career in game audio.

207
00:13:26,990 --> 00:13:29,472
And you may think, oh God, that is crazy.

208
00:13:30,530 --> 00:13:32,913
Do any of these relate to games?

209
00:13:32,913 --> 00:13:36,016
Those of you in the audience who may have come from stage,

210
00:13:36,016 --> 00:13:37,597
you're like, well, this is obvious.

211
00:13:37,597 --> 00:13:39,319
For those of you who are not,

212
00:13:39,319 --> 00:13:42,542
I'm gonna analyze one of my biggest career patterns

213
00:13:42,542 --> 00:13:44,644
before I worked in games, which was a 10-year sprint

214
00:13:44,644 --> 00:13:47,327
working as a touring stage manager in Pittsburgh

215
00:13:47,327 --> 00:13:49,029
for opera companies, ballet,

216
00:13:49,029 --> 00:13:51,511
and a bunch of modern art installations.

217
00:13:52,132 --> 00:13:57,397
And while working as a stage manager, I acquired many different types of skills

218
00:13:57,397 --> 00:14:01,502
that I realized later, when I eventually got in the game industry, were actually valid.

219
00:14:01,502 --> 00:14:03,784
So I'm going to analyze two different sets of skills.

220
00:14:03,784 --> 00:14:07,829
For those unfamiliar, there are hard skills and soft skills that you acquire.

221
00:14:08,309 --> 00:14:11,610
Hard skills are practical knowledge you learn hands-on.

222
00:14:11,610 --> 00:14:15,551
Software, handling rigging, things that actually

223
00:14:15,551 --> 00:14:17,451
were hard skills that I worked on in theater

224
00:14:17,451 --> 00:14:20,732
that I use in games, where I learned a ton about software,

225
00:14:20,732 --> 00:14:23,953
spreadsheet management, organization.

226
00:14:23,953 --> 00:14:26,033
Whenever you're working as a touring stage manager,

227
00:14:26,033 --> 00:14:28,574
you have to manage actors' calendars and rehearsal

228
00:14:28,574 --> 00:14:29,294
calendars.

229
00:14:29,294 --> 00:14:31,734
Anyone who works in freelance is a game audio person.

230
00:14:31,734 --> 00:14:36,376
Sometimes you have, oh, what, 700 color-coded calendars going

231
00:14:36,376 --> 00:14:37,916
at the same time with different deadlines.

232
00:14:38,877 --> 00:14:45,343
You learn about play testing when you work in theater because you do rehearsals and you try out stuff in front of audiences.

233
00:14:45,343 --> 00:14:47,705
And in games you do that a lot too.

234
00:14:47,705 --> 00:14:56,013
I learned a lot about working in different departments in software because I worked with some theater companies that had multimedia projection systems.

235
00:14:56,013 --> 00:15:03,260
And my knowledge of things that I learned through them prepared me for working side by side as an audio person with graphic people in the game industry.

236
00:15:03,841 --> 00:15:08,304
So those are some examples of actual software-based technical things.

237
00:15:08,304 --> 00:15:10,466
But one of the most important types of skills you can get

238
00:15:10,466 --> 00:15:14,729
that people often forget whenever they're trying to look at a career in games

239
00:15:14,729 --> 00:15:15,770
is soft skills.

240
00:15:15,770 --> 00:15:18,852
And whenever I say soft, I mean personal skills,

241
00:15:18,852 --> 00:15:21,654
ways to deal with people, emotions.

242
00:15:21,654 --> 00:15:24,056
A big word that floats around this conference is stress.

243
00:15:24,457 --> 00:15:29,541
burning out, learning how to say no whenever a task is impossible,

